"CORE_NARRATIVE: Traditional light field depth estimation is fundamentally bottlenecked by the **global Lambertian assumption**, causing severe failures in real-world scenes containing **non-Lambertian and mixed materials**. By introducing a **physical material perception mechanism** via **angular frequency analysis** and multi-view geometric consistency, our approach breaks this assumption to achieve **component-aware depth estimation** with high physical interpretability.\n\nINTRO_HOOK: Open with a striking physical example demonstrating how the **global Lambertian assumption** catastrophically fails when encountering **specular and scattering materials** in real-world scenes. This immediately establishes the **Lambertian assumption limitation** as the core bottleneck hindering the generalization of light field technology in **complex environments**.\n\nGAP_BRIDGE: Highlight that while existing methods attempt to implicitly suppress **non-Lambertian** artifacts, they fail to explicitly model the underlying optical physics, leaving the **global Lambertian assumption** intact. This gap necessitates our transition to rigorous **physical optical modeling** that explicitly decouples material properties for **high-precision depth estimation**.\n\nMETHOD_JUSTIFY: The design of the **dual-mask physical modeling** and **MRI-like angular frequency analysis** directly stems from the need to explicitly classify and decouple **Lambertian, specular, and scattering** components. Furthermore, the **Geometric Consistency Descriptor (GCD)** and adaptive energy adjustment are specifically formulated to resolve feature ambiguity caused by **non-Lambertian materials**, ensuring robust **component-aware depth estimation**.\n\nEXPERIMENT_VALIDATE: Validate the motivation by showcasing massive performance gains on datasets rich in **specular and scattering materials** (e.g., Apple, David), proving the efficacy of breaking the **global Lambertian assumption**. Ablation studies must explicitly quantify how the **physical material perception mechanism** and **GCD** improve physical interpretability and generalization in **mixed material** scenarios.\n\nCONCLUSION_ECHO: Conclude by reiterating that breaking the **global Lambertian assumption** through **physical optical modeling** represents a vital paradigm shift for light field depth estimation. Emphasize that achieving true **material perception** and **component-aware depth estimation** paves the way for deploying light field technology reliably in highly **complex, real-world environments**."